definition.value: The beta-anomer of ADP-D-glycero-D-manno-heptose.
Dianion of ADP-D-glycero-beta-D-manno-heptose arising from deprotonation of both free OH groups of the diphosphate.
A pyrrole formed via Maillard reaction of epsilon-aminocaproic acid with glucose.
A GDP-sugar in which the sugar component is D-glycero-alpha-D-manno-heptose.
An N-substituted pyrraline that is pyrraline in which the hydrogen attached to the pyrrole nitrogen has been replaced by a butyl group.
Dianion of GDP-D-glycero-alpha-D-manno-heptose arising from deprotonation of both free OH groups of the diphosphate.
An N-substituted pyrraline that is pyrraline in which the hydrogen attached to the pyrrole nitrogen has been replaced by a propyl group.
An N-substituted pyrraline formed via Maillard reaction of L-lysine with glucose.
An organophosphate oxoanion resulting from the removal of the three protons from the diphosphate group of 1,2-diacylglycerol 3-diphosphate.
An N-substituted pyrraline that is pyrraline in which the hydrogen attached to the pyrrole nitrogen has been replaced by a neopentyl (2,2-dimethylpropyl) group.
The 3'-O-methyl ether of tricetin.
A pyrrole having neopentyl-, formyl- and 1,2,3-trihydroxypropyl groups at positions 1-, 2- and 3- respectively.
A pyrrole carrying a formyl substituent at the 2-position.
The 3',5'-di-O-methyl ether of tricetin.  Known commonly as tricin, it is a constituent of rice bran and has been found to potently inhibit colon cancer cell growth.
A pyrrole carrying propyl and hydroxyacetyl groups at the 1- and 2-positions respectively.
A pyrrole carrying an acetyl substituent at the 2-position.
A pyrrole carrying methyl and acetyl substituents at the 1- and 2-positions respectively.
A furan carrying an acetyl substituent at the 2-position. Used in the production of the antibiotic cefuroxime (CHEBI:3515).
A furan carrying two hydroxymethyl substituents at the 2- and 5-positions.
The dianion resulting from the removal of the two protons from the diphosphate group of beta-D-glucosyl-(1->4)-N-acetyl-D-glucosaminyl undecaprenyl diphosphate.
A glyco-amino acid consisting of a D-fructosyl residue attached to the epsilon-amino group of N(alpha)-formyl-L-lysine.
A glycosylmannose consisting of beta-D-mannopyranose having a tyvelopyranosyl residue attached via an alpha-(1->3)-linkage
The alpha-anomer of the pyranose form of tyvelose.
A glycosylmannose consisting of alpha-D-mannopyranose having a paratopyranosyl residue attached via an alpha-(1->3)-linkage.
A member of the class of dimethylanilines that is N,N-dimethylaniline having a nitroso group at the 4-position.
A member of the class of dimethylanilines that is N,N-dimethylaniline having a hydroxylamino substituent at the 4-position.
The alpha-anomer of the pyranose form of abequose.

A broad-spectrum oxacephem antibiotic in which the oxazine ring is substituted with a tetrazolylthiomethyl group and the azetidinone ring carries methoxy and 2-carboxy-2-(4-hydroxyphenyl)acetamido substituents.
The alpha-anomer of the pyranose form of D-paratose.
A glycerophosphoinositol antigen having a 1-stearoyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho moiety attached at the 6-position of 1D-myo-inositol.
A 4,5-dihydropyrazole having p-sulfophenyl-, carboxy-, amino- and oxo substituents at the 1-, 3-, 4- and 5-positions respectively.
Trianion of 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycerol 3-diphosphate arising from deprotonation of the diphosphate OH groups.

Any EC 1.14.18.* (oxidoreductase acting on paired donors, miscellaneous compound as one donor, incorporating 1 atom of oxygen) inhibitor that interferes with the action of tyrosinase (monophenol monooxygenase), EC 1.14.18.1, an enzyme that catalyses the oxidation of phenols (such as tyrosine) and is widespread in plants and animals.
An sn-glycerol 3-phosphate having unspecified acyl groups at the 1- and 2-positions.
A chemical substance is a portion of matter of constant composition, composed of molecular entities of the same type or of different types.
The conjugate base of a 1-acyl-2-linoleoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine compound formed by deprotonation of the phosphate OH group.
The conjugate base of pelargonidin 3-O-rutinoside 5-O-beta-D-glucoside; major species at pH 7.3.
Dianion of D-glycero-D-manno-heptose 1-phosphate arising from deprotonation of both phosphate OH groups.
A pure substance is a chemical substance composed of multiple molecules, which are all of the same kind.
A mixture is a chemical substance composed of multiple molecules, at least two of which are of a different kind.
The conjugate base of 3-amino-4-hydroxybenzoic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
The conjugate base of laricitrin arising from deprotonation of the 3-OH group; major species at pH 7.3.
A steroid sulfate oxoanion and N-acylglycinate that is the dianion of sulfoglycolithocholic acid arising from deprotonation of carboxylic acid and sulfate functions; major species at pH 7.3.
A N-acylglycinate that is the conjugate base of glycolithocholic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
Trianion of UDP-6-sulfoquinovose arising from deprotonation of diphosphate and sulfonate OH groups; major species at pH 7.3.

A polypeptide comprising N-decanoyltryptophan, asparagine, aspartic acid, threonine, glycine, ornithine, aspartic acid, D-alanine, aspartic acid, glycine, D-serine, threo-3-methylglutamic acid and 3-anthraniloylalanine (also known as kynurinine) coupled in sequence and lactonised by condensation of the carboxylic acid group of the 3-anthraniloylalanine  with the alcohol group of the threonine residue.
